This song was frequently teased as an intro of X’s gaming videos on his YouTube channel prior to its release.

description.plain:
Jocelyn Flores was a friend of X who suffered from depression and committed suicide in May 2017, while staying with him in Florida for a photoshoot. He posted tweets about the situation, but they were later deleted. In an Instagram Live video, X detailed the events personally,

It was a devastating situation to deal with, it fucked me up so bad to where I wasn’t on social media for the last few days unless I was addressing something that I needed to. I never thought I would feel something for someone I barely knew that would fuck me up so bad just because I came from it

He previously dedicated the song “Revenge” to Jocelyn shortly after she died – he didn’t discuss her death on the track, although he wrote it in the song’s description on SoundCloud, “Rest in peace, Jocelyn, I will have my revenge upon the world.”

This song was performed over “im closing my eyes,” a potsu-produced song that samples the lyrics from Shiloh Dynasty’s “I Knew You So Well.” Two other tracks on 17 were also produced by potsu: “Everybody Dies In Their Nightmares” and “Carry On.”

On August 5, 2017, X uploaded a snippet of the song on his Snapchat story.

description.plain:
“Look At Me” was first released on December 30, 2015, via Soundcloud. It samples “Changes” by Mala.

The track received a second surge in popularity in late January 2017, when Drake previewed a song eventually released as “KMT,” which had a similar sounding flow.

After hearing the preview for “KMT,” X tweeted his frustration at the similarities. Drake denied stealing the flow, though he admitted there were similarities, prompting X to respond from jail, saying he would rather a big name artist like Drake help with his legal situation, rather than steal his flow and not give any credit.

Subsequently, in May 2017, “Look At Me!” was edited for better sound quality and placed on his Revenge mixtape, giving it a wider release on streaming services.

The controversial music video for “Look At Me!” released on September 12, 2017.

X tweeted that “Fuck Love” will be the only song off 17 that’ll be posted on Soundcloud. It was removed after X’s Soundcloud was hacked but later re-uploaded.

This song holds the record for most streams of any song on the SoundCloud platform with over 200 million plays.

description.plain:
X reminisces about his past wrongdoings, detailing a perhaps hypothetical conversation with Satan about the state of his soul.

He utilizes strong biblical references and language throughout this mini-masterpiece. His use of enjambment is also of note. Crafted to embody his evanescent spirit and dazed psyche, X splits what might otherwise be one line into many—exhibiting his fragmented mental state.

The song reflects X’s troubled upbringing, and how pain and sadness have plagued his brief time on this earth, as shown in the first half.

X learns that if he remains true to his selfish/evil side, that he can obtain what he really craves: power and wealth.

body.plain:
Jahseh Dwayne Ricardo Onfroy (born on January 23, 1998 in Plantation and raised in Lauderhill, Broward County, Florida)—better known by his stage name, XXXTENTACION (pronounced xxx-tenta-ción)—was an established force in the Florida Soundcloud rap scene. He became widely known for his uniquely raw and aggressive approach to music. X claimed that his varied artistic influences range from alternative rock bands such as Nirvana and The Fray to distinguished rappers like Lil Wayne and The Notorious B.I.G.

His breakout hit “Look At Me” was first released on Soundcloud in 2015, and then edited and re-released for his 2017 mixtape Revenge. This scored him an appearance in the XXL Freshman Class of 2017. He took the 10th spot, meaning he was voted in by the fans.

X frequently collaborated with his friend and fellow South Florida rapper, Ski Mask The Slump God. He met Ski in juvenile detention and founded the music collective, Members Only, with him.

X released his debut album, 17, in 2017 which peaked at #2 on the US Billboard 200. He followed that up with his second album, ? in early 2018. It became his first #1 album, and one of its two lead singles, “SAD!,” later became his first #1 song after his death.

On June 18, 2018, X was tragically shot to death in Deerfield Beach, Florida. According to police reports and surveillance recordings, multiple men planned to rob X after they discovered he was carrying a significant amount of cash with him. The men demanded that X leave his vehicle and hand over his money, but the rapper refused and was subsequently shot in the neck. The Broward County Sheriff’s Department later confirmed his death in a tweet. X was 20 years old.

In what is now an eerie message uploaded to his Instagram several months before his untimely death, X described how he wanted to be remembered:

If I’m gonna die or ever be a sacrifice, I wanna make sure that my life made at least 5 million kids happy or they found some sort of answers or resolve in my life.

Following his death, X’s mother Cleopatra Bernard posted a picture of a sonogram to her personal Instagram, previewing X’s unborn child. On November 24, 2018, an update was given by X’s mother about his baby, now named Gekuyme. This was a word X created on his Instagram meaning a “different state or next universe of thought.” On January 26, 2019, Gekyume was born.

In the time following the rapper’s passing, multiple posthumous verses and choruses were released to the public by several artists, including his first posthumous song with Trippie Redd. The track was titled “Ghost Busters” and features Ski Mask and Quavo. Other notable posthumous features include his records with Lil Peep and Lil Wayne.

X’s first posthumous album, SKINS, was released on December 7, 2018. The album was his shortest project to date and includes a sole feature from Kanye West. X’s final posthumous album, Bad Vibes Forever, was released on December 6 2019, and highlighted many old X songs released solely on his SoundCloud or previously unreleased snippets.

Information concerning an official documentary about X was teased on his Instagram  and YouTube channel one year after his death.
